\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Security and Privacy Engineering Principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT Department personnel and system developers shall apply agency-documented systems security and privacy engineering principles in the specification,
 design,
 development,
 implementation,
 and modification of all systems and system components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
System developers and IT Department personnel shall implement the privacy principle of minimization,
 using only the Personally Identifiable Information (PII) strictly necessary to perform system engineering and development tasks,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-8(33).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Developer Configuration Management,
 Testing,
 and Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
All software developed or acquired for Elko County systems shall be subject to controlled development practices that ensure the integrity,
 security,
 and quality of the resulting product.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Version Control and Configuration Integrity
\series default
:
 The IT Department shall require that all development artifacts,
 including source code,
 scripts,
 and configuration files,
 are maintained under version control.
 Changes to development tools and processes shall be documented and managed to facilitate supply chain risk assessment,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-10.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Developer Testing and Evaluation
\series default
:
 The IT Department shall require the developer to develop and implement a plan for ongoing security and privacy control assessments.
 Prior to deployment into any production environment,
 all software shall undergo security-focused testing including at minimum:
 functional testing,
 integration testing,
 regression testing,
 and information security testing.
 Test results shall be documented and provided to IT Department personnel as verifiable evidence of execution prior to system acceptance,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-11.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Development Process Standards
\series default
:
 IT Department personnel shall utilize approved development tools,
 standards,
 and methodologies.
 The Assistant IT Director shall review development processes,
 tools,
 tool options,
 and configurations at least annually (every 365 calendar days) to confirm they satisfy security and privacy requirements throughout the development life cycle,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-15.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 Flaw Remediation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IT Department shall require all system developers and External Service Providers to implement a verifiable flaw remediation process.
 All flaws identified during development,
 testing,
 or post-deployment operation shall be corrected according to the following severity-based schedule,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SA-11 and ECIO 
\series bold
Policy 
